div.p: To avoid a Table Scan every time a lock is requested, database engines use Intent Locks.

ol.li: TX A (Writer) wants to update one row. It places an IX (Intent Exclusive) lock on the Table.
TX B (Auditor) wants to read the entire table. It checks the Table Header for existing locks.
Since IX and S (Shared) are incompatible, TX B is blocked instantly at the header level without scanning millions of rows.
